Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryan4yin/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"eacf8b5c553c3167430a71521d85513a93451b23","author":{"name":"Ben Drucker","email":"b2c885d8d1f56a493dba4e46cab03e2d1f7398ea@gmail.com"},"message":"rename empty provider config test","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryan4yin/terraform/commits/eacf8b5c553c3167430a71521d85513a93451b23"},{"sha":"186eff96b8ee40f2da6f3288ade8868c25b168cc","author":{"name":"Ben Drucker","email":"b2c885d8d1f56a493dba4e46cab03e2d1f7398ea@gmail.com"},"message":"expand early return comment","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryan4yin/terraform/commits/186eff96b8ee40f2da6f3288ade8868c25b168cc"},{"sha":"a2c31088f446aecf2ba359dcde7526c6b0a4adb5","author":{"name":"Ben Drucker","email":"b2c885d8d1f56a493dba4e46cab03e2d1f7398ea@gmail.com"},"message":"call configBody.Content","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryan4yin/terraform/commits/a2c31088f446aecf2ba359dcde7526c6b0a4adb5"},{"sha":"7e11b9792309a60113b6e35f46c340db6656fe42","author":{"name":"Ben Drucker","email":"b2c885d8d1f56a493dba4e46cab03e2d1f7398ea@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge remote-tracking branch 'origin/master' into validate-ignore-empty-provider","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryan4yin/terraform/commits/7e11b9792309a60113b6e35f46c340db6656fe42"},{"sha":"2549e53aed1151532001760be9215a9a16971c1f","author":{"name":"Ben Drucker","email":"b2c885d8d1f56a493dba4e46cab03e2d1f7398ea@gmail.com"},"message":"add backend refresh test with provider config","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/ryan4yin/terraform/commits/2549e53aed1151532001760be9215a9a16971c1f"}]

Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MikeOwino/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

This bug was introduced in de37b1e - TF statically loads a bunch of TF_VARIANT decoders,
but then it dynamically loads the same (or some) libraries and overwrites global lists,
this bug has actually been there forever, but no one uses TF_VARIANT to store bool or int32,
so when those got overwritten (actually, lost), no one cared.

But variant decoder for TensorList got lost and reverting de37b1e should have fixed that.
This patch fixed the bug by explicitly calling single static function defined not in a header, but in C code.

Please see https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/44428 for how
this bug was found and which fix worked for macos, the second commit

library loading, thus TensorList got different RTTI ID and decoder in

Change-Id: I624a29a5ccc5baf6b7e34268082c0b0ea0c96a5c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/8106d4b5fa426a09c205b38d2ded8a6ac57834be"},{"sha":"a139793bbbfc65b5057f6a570a5b129f3fcaab64","author":{"name":"Yang Chen","email":"b1c859b0203793580f6fafdc9e88d8c10428cc59@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Pull from iterators with a dedicated prefetching thread.

tf.data service workers pull data from iterators from a gRPC-created rpc
handler thread. The thread name often changes across calls, resulting in messy
xprof traces with loads of grpcpp_sync_server threads, with one GetNext call in
each thread. It is cleaner to use a dedicated thread to fetch elements for each
iterator.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/testkevinbonz/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's

Adds Gradient implementations and tests for the following ops:

 - SplitV
 - ConcatV2
 - BroadcastTo
 - Tile
 - GatherV2
 - Cumsum
 - Cast
 - FusedBatchNormV3
 - Conv2DBackpropInput

Most implementations are translated from the python version, although ConcatV2 copies the implementation from tensorflow/core/ops/array_grad.cc

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/guyuchao3/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

This bug was introduced in de37b1e - TF statically loads a bunch of TF_VARIANT decoders,
but then it dynamically loads the same (or some) libraries and overwrites global lists,
this bug has actually been there forever, but no one uses TF_VARIANT to store bool or int32,
so when those got overwritten (actually, lost), no one cared.

But variant decoder for TensorList got lost and reverting de37b1e should have fixed that.
This patch fixed the bug by explicitly calling single static function defined not in a header, but in C code.

this bug was found and which fix worked for macos, the second commit

Logging to daemon logs every time there's an error with a log driver can be
problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

Instead, it's preferable to limit the rate at which log driver errors are allowed
to be written. By default, this limit is 333 entries per second max.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

Adds Gradient implementations and tests for the following ops:

 - SplitV
 - ConcatV2
 - BroadcastTo
 - Tile
 - GatherV2
 - Cumsum
 - Cast
 - FusedBatchNormV3
 - Conv2DBackpropInput
 - DepthwiseConv2dNative

Most implementations are translated from the python version, although ConcatV2 copies the implementation from tensorflow/core/ops/array_grad.cc

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

[{"sha":"cd1663813e54f5afe0c265b1ac32ed9a993c82b9","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"getmodules: Beginnings of a new package about Terraform module packages

This new package aims to encapsulate all of our interactions with
go-getter to fetch remote module packages, to ensure that the rest of
Terraform will only use the small subset of go-getter functionality that
our modern module installer uses.

In older versions of Terraform, go-getter was the entire implementation
of module installation, but along the way we found that several aspects of
its design are poor fit for Terraform's needs, and so now we're using it
as just an implementation detail of Terraform's handling of remote module
packages only, hiding it behind this wrapper API which exposes only
the services that our module installer needs.

This new package isn't actually used yet, but in a later commit we will
change all of the other callers to go-getter to only work indirectly
through this package, so that this will be the only package that actually
imports the go-getter packages.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/cd1663813e54f5afe0c265b1ac32ed9a993c82b9"},{"sha":"95bbde857b232522e63c8513313b15b837d3be8c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"addrs: Representation of module source addresses

We've previously had the syntax and representation of module source
addresses pretty sprawled around the codebase and intermingled with other
systems such as the module installer.

I've created a factored-out implementation here with the intention of
enabling some later refactoring to centralize the address parsing as part
of configuration decoding, and thus in turn allow the parsing result to
be seen by other parts of Terraform that interact with configuration
objects, so that they can more robustly handle differences between local
and remote modules, and can present module addresses consistently in the
UI.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/95bbde857b232522e63c8513313b15b837d3be8c"},{"sha":"2e4987e19256db41ceb3c213a0429dd6f5ba3497","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"wip new module source address type","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/2e4987e19256db41ceb3c213a0429dd6f5ba3497"}]

problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

Instead, it's preferable to limit the rate at which log driver errors are allowed
to be written. By default, this limit is 333 entries per second max.

Change-Id: Ic2c1ae62dd9eef00cd497f481a1264e362c26f17","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/amandal-cad/tensorflow/commits/ce84c661ef8e223a7d76d69d79ce0f26c216c3b9"},{"sha":"b46b63828bd45d89258de89fe192a5a866b4dcba","author":{"name":"Jonas Ohlsson","email":"005214b216f8398cf48e70825438ba6e008e9b40@arm.com"},"message":"Facilitate building on Windows

Updates to facilitate building on Windows systems, via for instance
Git Bash.
- fix: Changed use of TMPDIR to TEMPDIR in flatbuffers download.
       Variable TMPDIR have special meaning in mktemp, and if set in
       the environment it will be used as template for the second call
       to mktemp. As the temporary directory is removed before the
       second call it would fail if TMPDIR was present in the
       environment.
 - Added download of the Windows version of GNU Arm Embedded Toolchain.
 - In the cortex_m target files, do not download the GNU Arm Embedded
   Toolchain if a TARGET_TOOLCHAIN_ROOT is set.

Signed-off-by: Jonas Ohlsson <jonas.ohlsson@arm.com>

Change-Id: I624a29a5ccc5baf6b7e34268082c0b0ea0c96a5c","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/8106d4b5fa426a09c205b38d2ded8a6ac57834be"},{"sha":"a139793bbbfc65b5057f6a570a5b129f3fcaab64","author":{"name":"Yang Chen","email":"b1c859b0203793580f6fafdc9e88d8c10428cc59@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Pull from iterators with a dedicated prefetching thread.

tf.data service workers pull data from iterators from a gRPC-created rpc
handler thread. The thread name often changes across calls, resulting in messy
xprof traces with loads of grpcpp_sync_server threads, with one GetNext call in
each thread. It is cleaner to use a dedicated thread to fetch elements for each
iterator.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Geolem/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

[{"sha":"87c1208e06fcb4177c7d81d6297eaedc16383357","author":{"name":"Mahmoud Abuzaina","email":"a2ed0f6fa01f715ca5a92264281888c73ba9e3c6@intel.com"},"message":"Enable INT8 in native format mode","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/87c1208e06fcb4177c7d81d6297eaedc16383357"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

some TF libraries got loaded twice and some global variables got overwritten.

This bug was introduced in de37b1e - TF statically loads a bunch of TF_VARIANT decoders,
but then it dynamically loads the same (or some) libraries and overwrites global lists,
this bug has actually been there forever, but no one uses TF_VARIANT to store bool or int32,
so when those got overwritten (actually, lost), no one cared.

But variant decoder for TensorList got lost and reverting de37b1e should have fixed that.
This patch fixed the bug by explicitly calling single static function defined not in a header, but in C code.

[{"sha":"cf259eb8a04c44844b46897949dad7fdfc71230c","author":{"name":"Anuj Varma","email":"0e2a6ab4c7f8325d615a94103fa4c3a509075615@thumbtack.com"},"message":"Wait for `run` goroutine to exit before `Close`

The underlying Loggers Close() function can be called with the the
run() goroutine still writing to the driver. This is causing the
fluentd-golang-logger to panic cause it doesn't defensively check
for the closing of the channel before writing to it.
It relies on the docker daemon to keep the contract of not calling Log()
if Close() has already been called.

Contributions by: James Johnston <james.johnston@thumbtack.com>
                  Nathan Wong <nathanw@thumbtack.com>

Signed-off-by: Tianon Gravi <admwiggin@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bearstech/moby/commits/d72722f97c336dd8f8e11e31776a9c6fca976e0d"},{"sha":"fb5a9ec741c4a2246624b694d88db2e5fabc9118","author":{"name":"Angel Velazquez","email":"e7be62313d96a6aa5d44f8f6bc3f3eab388c04d9@amazon.com"},"message":"Limit the rate at which logger errors are logged into daemon logs

Logging to daemon logs every time there's an error with a log driver can be
problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

Instead, it's preferable to limit the rate at which log driver errors are allowed
to be written. By default, this limit is 333 entries per second max.

[{"sha":"fb5a9ec741c4a2246624b694d88db2e5fabc9118","author":{"name":"Angel Velazquez","email":"e7be62313d96a6aa5d44f8f6bc3f3eab388c04d9@amazon.com"},"message":"Limit the rate at which logger errors are logged into daemon logs

problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk

Adds Gradient implementations and tests for the following ops:

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

each thread. It is cleaner to use a dedicated thread to fetch elements for each
iterator.

Adds Gradient implementations and tests for the following ops:

 - SplitV
 - ConcatV2
 - BroadcastTo
 - Tile
 - GatherV2
 - Cumsum
 - Cast
 - FusedBatchNormV3
 - Conv2DBackpropInput
 - DepthwiseConv2dNative

Most implementations are translated from the python version, although ConcatV2 copies the implementation from tensorflow/core/ops/array_grad.cc

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

[{"sha":"87c1208e06fcb4177c7d81d6297eaedc16383357","author":{"name":"Mahmoud Abuzaina","email":"a2ed0f6fa01f715ca5a92264281888c73ba9e3c6@intel.com"},"message":"Enable INT8 in native format mode","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/87c1208e06fcb4177c7d81d6297eaedc16383357"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

DevTools now 'untrack' Fibers (cleans up the ID-to-Fiber mapping) after a slight delay in order to support a Fast Refresh edge case:
1. Component type is updated and Fast Refresh schedules an update+remount.
2. flushPendingErrorsAndWarningsAfterDelay() runs, sees the old Fiber is no longer mounted (it's been disconnected by Fast Refresh), and calls untrackFiberID() to clear it from the Map.
3. React flushes pending passive effects before it runs the next render, which logs an error or warning, which causes a new ID to be generated for this Fiber.
4. DevTools now tries to unmount the old Component with the new ID.

Signed-off-by: Cam <gh@sparr.email>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joakimr-axis/moby/commits/e57a365ab1a1b5f30b9cc04e2365448868ae5b4f"},{"sha":"cf259eb8a04c44844b46897949dad7fdfc71230c","author":{"name":"Anuj Varma","email":"0e2a6ab4c7f8325d615a94103fa4c3a509075615@thumbtack.com"},"message":"Wait for `run` goroutine to exit before `Close`

The underlying Loggers Close() function can be called with the the
run() goroutine still writing to the driver. This is causing the
fluentd-golang-logger to panic cause it doesn't defensively check
for the closing of the channel before writing to it.
It relies on the docker daemon to keep the contract of not calling Log()
if Close() has already been called.

Contributions by: James Johnston <james.johnston@thumbtack.com>
                  Nathan Wong <nathanw@thumbtack.com>

Signed-off-by: Tianon Gravi <admwiggin@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joakimr-axis/moby/commits/d72722f97c336dd8f8e11e31776a9c6fca976e0d"},{"sha":"fb5a9ec741c4a2246624b694d88db2e5fabc9118","author":{"name":"Angel Velazquez","email":"e7be62313d96a6aa5d44f8f6bc3f3eab388c04d9@amazon.com"},"message":"Limit the rate at which logger errors are logged into daemon logs

Logging to daemon logs every time there's an error with a log driver can be
problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

Instead, it's preferable to limit the rate at which log driver errors are allowed
to be written. By default, this limit is 333 entries per second max.

Other Unix platforms (e.g. Darwin) are also affected by the Go
runtime sending SIGURG.

This patch changes how we match the signal by just looking for the
"URG" name, which should handle any platform that has this signal
defined in the SignalMap.

[{"sha":"fb5a9ec741c4a2246624b694d88db2e5fabc9118","author":{"name":"Angel Velazquez","email":"e7be62313d96a6aa5d44f8f6bc3f3eab388c04d9@amazon.com"},"message":"Limit the rate at which logger errors are logged into daemon logs

Logging to daemon logs every time there's an error with a log driver can be
problematic since daemon logs can grow rapidly, potentially exhausting disk
space.

Instead, it's preferable to limit the rate at which log driver errors are allowed
to be written. By default, this limit is 333 entries per second max.

Previously, DevTools recursed over both children and siblings during mount. This caused potential stack overflows when there were a lot of children (e.g. a list containing many items).

Given the following example component tree:

       A
    B  C  D
    E     F
          G

A method that recurses for every child and sibling leads to a max depth of 6:

    A
    A -> B
    A -> B -> E
    A -> B -> C
    A -> B -> C -> D
    A -> B -> C -> D -> F
    A -> B -> C -> D -> F -> G

The stack gets deeper as the tree gets either deeper or wider.

A method that recurses for every child and iterates over siblings leads to a max depth of 4:

    A
    A -> B
    A -> B -> E
    A -> C
    A -> D
    A -> D -> F
    A -> D -> F -> G

The stack gets deeper as the tree gets deeper but is resilient to wide trees (e.g. lists containing many items).","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eps1lon/react/commits/a0d6b155dc3a182162b9f91baac33df39d7919df"},{"sha":"7edd6281344a35519ca36b8a8280e7ba37187004","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Removed (deleted) tracing fixture test from relesae scripts","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eps1lon/react/commits/7edd6281344a35519ca36b8a8280e7ba37187004"},{"sha":"2a7bb4154809f1f4e17ffbdde1342bd4ce91ea37","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Preparing DevTools 4.12.4 -> 4.13.0 release (#21378)","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eps1lon/react/commits/2a7bb4154809f1f4e17ffbdde1342bd4ce91ea37"},{"sha":"207d4c3a535d4624f17634baa6bfe613f5f3e4e6","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Revert "Support nesting of startTransition and flushSync (alt) (#21149)"

This reverts commit 2e7aceeb5c8b6e5c61174c0e9731e263e956e445.

If a discrete render results in passive effects, we should flush them
synchronously at the end of the current task so that the result is
immediately observable. For example, if a passive effect adds an event
listener, the listener will be added before the next input.

We don't need to do this for effects that don't have discrete/sync
priority, because we assume they are not order-dependent and do not
need to be observed by external systems.

For legacy mode, we will maintain the existing behavior, since it hasn't
been reported as an issue, and we'd have to do additional work to
distinguish "legacy default sync" from "discrete sync" to prevent all
passive effects from being treated this way.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/eps1lon/react/commits/7bac7607a764074e66dd57c68c09ec5cc898f4a5"},{"sha":"e7e0a90bd8558af16bb6aa278097536d9b69643c","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Revert "Fix: flushSync changes priority inside effect (#21122)"

This reverts commit 0e3c7e1d62efb6238b69e5295d45b9bd2dcf9181.

When called from inside an effect, flushSync cannot synchronously flush
its updates because React is already working. So we fire a warning.

However, we should still change the priority of the updates to sync so
that they flush at the end of the current task.

This reverts commit 8ed0c85bf174ce6e501be62d9ccec1889bbdbce1.

The host tree is a cyclical structure. Leaking a single DOM node can
retain a large amount of memory. React-managed DOM nodes also point
back to a fiber tree.

Perf testing suggests that disconnecting these fields has a big memory
impact. That suggests leaks in non-React code but since it's hard to
completely eliminate those, it may still be worth the extra work to
clear these fields.

I'm moving this to level 2 to confirm whether this alone is responsible
for the memory savings, or if there are other fields that are retaining
large amounts of memory.

connected to fibers, except at the root of the whole tree, which is
easy to disconnect on deletion. So in that world, we likely won't have

Adds Gradient implementations and tests for the following ops:

 - SplitV
 - ConcatV2
 - BroadcastTo
 - Tile
 - GatherV2
 - Cumsum
 - Cast
 - FusedBatchNormV3
 - Conv2DBackpropInput
 - DepthwiseConv2dNative

Most implementations are translated from the python version, although ConcatV2 copies the implementation from tensorflow/core/ops/array_grad.cc

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/clayne/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add additional Gradient Operations to Tensorflow C++

Adds Gradient implementations and tests for the following ops:

 - SplitV
 - ConcatV2
 - BroadcastTo
 - Tile
 - GatherV2
 - Cumsum
 - Cast
 - FusedBatchNormV3
 - Conv2DBackpropInput
 - DepthwiseConv2dNative

Most implementations are translated from the python version, although ConcatV2 copies the implementation from tensorflow/core/ops/array_grad.cc

PiperOrigin-RevId: 376259716
Change-Id: I0d30a7deda92a514e1fe82d70951a83a1bc9b7dd","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jiankaiwang/tensorflow/commits/bf3d89b1e8bc5e00271c2fbd57a8b3ff55d48462"},{"sha":"f60e73456ed6c0e121a9d2b308f9c9f8f9a3cdb7","author":{"name":"Justin Lebar","email":"631d11d9fe908fc8f04b5865032c3043cb48fdfb@google.com"},"message":"Support parsing ConvolutionDimensionNumbers with "unknown" dimensions.

For e.g. a 2D cudnn int8x4 / int8x32 convolutions, we have five dimensions:
batch, feature, height, width, and "vect", the vectorized feature dim of size 4
or 32.

Right now we don't explicitly represent the vect dim in
ConvolutionDimensionNumbers, because only cudnn convolutions, which are
custom-calls, use this dimension.  It wouldn't make sense to add it for all of
XLA.

But the mere implicit presence of this extra dimension on these custom-calls
breaks ConvolutionDimensionNumbers parsing/stringification (in kind of a
spectacular way: we get heap overflows)

With this patch, we allow the dims in ConvolutionDimensionNumbers to be
noncontiguous.  We represent the missing dimensions with '?'.  That's
sufficient for our cudnn needs.
